snippet: The nation’s housing policy for the poor can feel like a giant lottery. Sometimes it actually is a lottery.

headline.print_headline: What the Royal Bride-to-Be Represents to Black Londoners
headline.main: What Meghan Markle Means to Black Britons

snippet: Black Londoners like Tshego Lengolo, 11, suddenly have a reason to tune in to Britain’s royal family: They can see a version of themselves in the woman Prince Harry is set to marry.

headline.main: Clashing Views on Iran Reflect a New Balance of Power in the Cabinet

snippet: John R. Bolton, the new national security adviser, is on the rise, and Defense Secretary Jim Mattis appears more isolated. The new secretary of state, Mike Pompeo, may be the man in the middle.

headline.print_headline: His College Saw Despair. His Parents Didn’t, Until It Was Too Late.
headline.main: His College Knew of His Despair. His Parents Didn’t, Until It Was Too Late.

snippet: Hamilton College knew that one of its students was in deep distress before he killed himself. His parents believe they should have been told.

headline.print_headline: At Toys ‘R’ Us, Bankruptcy Was Painful, But Not for All
headline.main: At Toys ‘R’ Us, a $200 Million Debt Problem Could Lead to $348 Million in Fees

headline.print_headline: Federal Tax Cuts Give Many States A Cash Windfall
headline.main: Federal Tax Cuts Leave States in a Bind

snippet: The federal tax law had the unintended effect of giving states a tax windfall. Now, states must weigh whether to spend the money or give it back to residents.
